name: Domain Name Finder
description:
Overview:
Finding a domain name that fits your brand shouldn’t take hours of searching and failed checks. The Domain Name Finder Agent turns your pitch into hundreds of creative, brand-ready domain ideas—filtered by live availability so every result is actionable.

How It Works
1. Input your product pitch, company name, or core keywords.
2. The agent analyzes brand tone, audience, and industry context.
3. It generates a list of unique, memorable domains that match your criteria.
4. All names are pre-filtered for real-time availability, so you can register immediately.


Business Value
Save hours of guesswork and eliminate dead ends. Accelerate brand launches, startup naming, and campaign creation with ready-to-claim domains.


Key Use Cases
• Startup Founders: Quickly find brand-ready domains for MVP launches or rebrands.
• Marketers: Test name options across campaigns with instant availability data.
• Entrepreneurs: Validate ideas faster with instant domain options.
instructions: Pitch your website idea, run the agent, then check back in 10 mins for your bespoke set of unregistered domain names - ranked by estimated valuation and relevance to your pitch.

input_default.prompt:
Generate a creative and relevant list of possible domain names that could be available (unregistered) for the product described by the given product pitch. Prioritize short, single-word English .com domains that closely relate to the product or its key features, as these are the most valuable. Only suggest .com domains. Avoid suggesting long or awkward names; names that sound like real English words but may be invented are acceptable if memorable and brandable. Do not include off-topic, or low-value gibberish names.

Before listing any domains, internally consider:
- What words or ideas are most core to the product pitch?
- Which synonyms, metaphors, or conceptual connections would make good brands?
- What domains are likely to realistically be available and not already taken?
- Are there any exceptional reasons to consider a non-.com extension?
- Whether the domains are concise, attractive, and easy to remember/pronounce.

Output only the domains in a comma-separated list, enclosed in <domains> XML tags, with no additional commentary or explanation.

Format:
<domains>example1.com,example2.com,example3.com</domains>

Example Input:
 "A voice-based fitness app"

Example Output:
<domains>votone.com,soundgym.com,voicetrain.com,fitchant.com</domains>
(Realistic use cases may generate ~500k high-quality domains per prompt.)

Edge Cases & Special Considerations:
- Never generate multi-word domains with dashes or excessive length.
- If a non-.com TLD is used, justify internally that it is a natural fit (e.g., ".ai" for an artificial intelligence SaaS).
- Exclude domains that are likely to be heavily trademarked or existing brands.
- The output must always be ONLY the XML tag with comma-separated domains.
- Aim to write at least 500 domains
- NEVER comment inside the <domains> csv, otherwise the csv will be corrupted and the workflow will completely break. If you want to make a comment, leave a <comment> xml set OUTSIDE the </domains> xml set with your comments. No matter what do not break this rule.

Here is the product pitch you will be working with:
<product_pitch>
{{product_pitch | safe}}
</product_pitch>


REMINDER: Focus on creative, concise, high value .com domains aligned with the product pitch; output only as <domains>example.com,example2.com</domains>

You are a domain valuation expert tasked with ranking a list of domain names based on their value and relevance to a specific product. You will be provided with two key pieces of information:

1. A product pitch:
<product_pitch>
{{product_pitch | safe}}
</product_pitch>

2. A list of domain names to rank:
<domain_list>
{{domains | safe}}
</domain_list>

Your task is to analyze these domains and rank them based on two primary factors:
1. The inherent value of the domain name (most important)
2. The relevance and potential value of the domain for the specific product described in the product pitch

Please follow these steps:

1. Read the product pitch carefully and extract key product features and target audience information. List these in <product_analysis> tags.

2. Identify relevant keywords for the product based on the pitch. List these in <keywords> tags.

3. For each domain in the provided list - carefully consider it, then pick your top 10 domains from the list for the following analysis:
   a. Evaluate the domain based on the following factors:
      - Length (number of characters)
      - Memorability
      - Brandability
      - Keyword relevance
      - TLD (Top-Level Domain)
      - Potential commercial value

   b. Calculate a Domain Quality Score (1-10) using the following method:
      - Length Score (LS):
        10: 1–4 chars
        9: 5
        8: 6
        7: 7
        6: 8
        5: 9
        4: 10
        3: 11–12
        2: 13–14
        1: 15+

      - Word Score (WS):
        * Base (BWC): 1 word =5, 2 words =4, 3w=3, 4w=2, 5+ words =1
        * Quality Modifier (WQM): +1 English dictionary word, 0 common/brandable, –1 meh brand/obscure foreign, –2 unpronounceable
        * Word Score (WS) = clamp(BWC + WQM, 1–5)×2

      - Penalties: –1 hyphen, –1 number, –0.5 triple letter

      - Final Score = clamp(round(0.6×WS + 0.4×LS + penalties), 1–10)

   c. Consider how the domain relates to the product described in the product pitch.

Wrap your analysis in a single set of <domain_analysis> tags. 
Include the following for each domain:
1. Verify that the domain is present in the original list provided.
2. A table with the following columns: Factor, Calculated Score, Justification.
3. The calculated Domain Quality Score, showing each step of the calculation.
4. An explanation of how the domain relates to the product pitch.

After evaluating your potential top 10 domains, present your final ranking as a newline-separated list of domains inside a single complete set of <domains> XML tags. Ensure that only domains from the original list are included in your ranking.

If there are more than 30 domains in the list, just list your top 30.

Example output format:

<domains>
domain1.com
domain2.net
domain3.org
</domains>

Please proceed with your evaluation and ranking of the provided domain list.

input_default.format:
#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
check_domains_simple_com.py — Check .com domain availability via RDAP.

How to use:
1) Put comma-separated .com domains into DOMAINS_TEXT below.
   - Each comma-delimited token must be an exact .com domain (e.g., "foo.com").
   - Anything that is not a valid .com domain counts as an input error.
2) Run: python3 check_domains_simple_com.py
3) Output summary sections and lists of available/unavailable/error tokens.
"""

from __future__ import annotations

import re
from concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor, as_completed
from typing import Dict, List, Tuple

import requests
from requests.adapters import HTTPAdapter

try:
    from urllib3.util.retry import Retry  # type: ignore
except Exception:  # Retry optional
    Retry = None  # type: ignore

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# 📝 Paste your names/domains here (commas and/or newlines are fine).
DOMAINS_TEXT = """{{DOMAINS | safe}}"""
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------

# Concurrency / networking
WORKERS = 80
TIMEOUT = 12.0

HEADERS = {
    "Accept": "application/rdap+json, application/json;q=0.9, */*;q=0.1",
    "User-Agent": "domain-checker/1.0 (+https://example.com)",
}

# Verisign RDAP for .com
COM_ENDPOINT = "https://rdap.verisign.com/com/v1/domain/{}"


def normalize_label(s: str) -> str:
    """Lowercase and keep only a–z and 0–9."""
    return re.sub(r"[^a-z0-9]", "", s.lower())

COM_DOMAIN_RE = re.compile(r"^(?=.{1,253}$)(?!-)[a-z0-9](?:[a-z0-9-]{0,61}[a-z0-9])?\.com$")


def domains_from_text(text: str) -> Tuple[List[str], List[str]]:
    """Parse comma-separated tokens; accept only exact .com domains.

    Returns (valid_domains, invalid_tokens).
    """
    tokens: List[str] = []
    for part in (text or "").split(","):
        val = part.strip()
        if val:
            tokens.append(val)

    valid_domains: List[str] = []
    invalid_tokens: List[str] = []
    for token in tokens:
        s = token.strip().lower()
        if COM_DOMAIN_RE.match(s):
            # De-dup preserving order for domains only
            if s not in valid_domains:
                valid_domains.append(s)
        else:
            invalid_tokens.append(token)

    return valid_domains, invalid_tokens


def build_session(pool_size: int) -> requests.Session:
    session = requests.Session()
    session.headers.update(HEADERS)
    adapter_kwargs = {"pool_connections": pool_size, "pool_maxsize": pool_size}
    if Retry is not None:
        retry = Retry(
            total=3,
            backoff_factor=0.3,
            status_forcelist=(429, 500, 502, 503, 504),
            allowed_methods=("GET",),
            raise_on_status=False,
        )
        adapter = HTTPAdapter(max_retries=retry, **adapter_kwargs)
    else:
        adapter = HTTPAdapter(**adapter_kwargs)
    session.mount("https://", adapter)
    session.mount("http://", adapter)
    return session


def rdap_lookup_com(domain: str, session: requests.Session) -> Dict[str, str]:
    """Return {'domain': str, 'status': 'AVAILABLE'|'REGISTERED'|'ERROR'|'UNKNOWN_xx'}."""
    url = COM_ENDPOINT.format(domain)
    try:
        r = session.get(url, timeout=TIMEOUT)
    except requests.RequestException as e:
        return {"domain": domain, "status": "ERROR", "error": str(e)}
    if r.status_code == 404:
        return {"domain": domain, "status": "AVAILABLE"}
    if r.status_code == 200:
        return {"domain": domain, "status": "REGISTERED"}
    return {"domain": domain, "status": f"UNKNOWN_{r.status_code}", "error": r.text[:200].replace("\n", " ")}


def main() -> int:
    domains, invalid_tokens = domains_from_text(DOMAINS_TEXT)
    if not domains and not invalid_tokens:
        return 0

    # Preserve input order
    domain_to_index: Dict[str, int] = {d: i for i, d in enumerate(domains)}

    # Connection pool
    pool_size = max(1, min(WORKERS, len(domains)))
    session = build_session(pool_size)

    rows = []
    with ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=pool_size) as executor:
        futs = {executor.submit(rdap_lookup_com, d, session): d for d in domains}
        for fut in as_completed(futs):
            rows.append(fut.result())

    # Restore input order
    rows.sort(key=lambda r: domain_to_index.get(r.get("domain", ""), 10**9))

    # Group domains by availability
    available = []
    unavailable = []
    errors = []
    for r in rows:
        if r.get("status") == "AVAILABLE" and r.get("domain"):
            available.append(r["domain"])
        elif r.get("status") == "REGISTERED" and r.get("domain"):
            unavailable.append(r["domain"])
        elif r.get("domain"):
            errors.append(r["domain"])

    # Include input parsing errors (non-.com tokens)
    errors.extend(invalid_tokens)

    # Print in requested format
    print("<results_summary>")
    total = len(available) + len(unavailable)
    print(f" I checked {total} domains for you.")
    print(f"Domains available to register now: {len(available)}")
    print(f"Domains already registered: {len(unavailable)}")
    print("</results_summary>")
    print("<available>")
    for domain in available:
        print(domain)
    print("</available>")
    print("<unavailable>")
    for domain in unavailable:
        print(domain)
    print("</unavailable>")
    print("<error>")
    for domain in errors:
        print(domain)
    print("</error>")

    return 0


if __name__ == "__main__":
    _ = main()

This could either be due to the input you provided, or an error in the system.

Please try again, but if this keeps happening please report it!

input_default.format:
### Summary

{{ summary 
   | replace('\r\n', '\n')
   | replace('\n', '  \n') }}

### How This List Is Ranked

The suggestions are **ranked from best fit to broader options** based on:
- **Fit with your pitch** (topic match, tone, audience)
- **Brandability** (memorability, uniqueness, ease to say/spell)
- **Clarity & length** (short, unambiguous, no filler)
- **Domain quality** (clean .com bias; no hyphens/numbers)
- **Noise penalties** (awkward word combos or ambiguity)

> Tip: The top 5 are usually the “buy now” candidates. If you love a lower-ranked name, go for it—the ranking is guidance, not a rule.

### Domain Suggestions (Ranked)

{{ ranked_domains_block
   | replace('\r\n', '\n')
   | replace('\n', '  \n') }}


### What to Do Next

The domain names listed above are still available for registration. To claim one, purchase it from a domain registrar (a company that sells and manages domain names). Availability can change quickly, so check out promptly.

**Popular registrars:**
- [GoDaddy](https://www.godaddy.com/) — one of the largest registrars.  
- [Namecheap](https://www.namecheap.com/) — transparent pricing and easy UI.  
- [Domain.com](https://www.domain.com/) — long-standing, straightforward.  
- [Dynadot](https://www.dynadot.com/) — clean, low-friction checkout.  
- [IONOS](https://www.ionos.com/domains) — competitive first-year pricing.

**Steps:**
1. Pick your favourite from the top of the list.  
2. Add to cart and check out — confirm the price — usually **$10–15 per year** 
3. In your registrar dashboard, set up **DNS / name servers** to point the domain to your website or email.  
4. (Optional) Consider grabbing close variants or common misspellings for brand protection.
